Notation:
  "pxl"         : Represents the number of LEDs for one written output color.
                  Needed because LED strips often are only controllable in
                  consecutive groups of 3, 5, sometimes 36 or more LEDs for
                  COB strips, etc.
  ℝ             : float
  ℤ             : integer
  ℕ             : integer≥0
  𝔹             : boolean
  𝑆             : string, UTF-8 encoded
  [X,Y,Z]       : An array with index 0 being of type X, index 1 of type Y, etc.
  [X,?Y,Z]      : An array that looks like either [X,Y,Z] or [X,Z]
                  Shorthand for [X,...∪{[],[Y]},Z]
  [X,...Y]      : An array with index 0 being of type X, and the contents of
                    type Y (which must ultimately evaluate to an array) placed
                    in line afterwards.
                  E.g. [5,...[6,7]] = [5,6,7]
                  E.g. [𝑆,...*ℕ] = [some string, some integer X, some integer Y, etc.]
  𝑇             : Type
  𝑇[X,Y]        : Type that meets qualifications X and Y
                    E.g. ℕ[5≤x≤10,x≠7] has possible values 5,6,8,9,10
  ∪{X,Y}        : Either type X or type Y
                    E.g. ∪{ℕ,𝑆} is an integer or a string
  ⟨X↦Y⟩         : A key-value pair. Only makes sense in the context of ultimately
                    ending up inside a dict
  𝐷[⟨X↦Y⟩,⟨Z↦W⟩]: Dict (or object) with:
                    A key-value pair mapping type X mapping to type Y
                    A key-value pair mapping type Z mapping to type W
                  Note that these work exactly like lists with the two added requirements,
                    1. All element are key-value pairs
                    2. There are no elements with the same key
  𝑆_strip       : 𝑆 with no preceeding or trailing whitespace
  𝑆[ⴽ"abc"]     : 𝑆 that fully matches the regex "abc"
  *𝑇            : An array of some type
  *(X)𝑇         : An array of some type with qualifications X on the array itself
                    E.g. *(0<len≤10)ℤ is an array of at least 1, but no more than 10, integers

Types:
  TOKEN     = 𝑆[6≤len≤64]
  UUID      = 𝑆[ⴽ"[a-zA-Z0-9]{8,64}"]
  NAME      = 𝑆[1≤len≤64]
  RGB       = ℕ[0x000000≤x≤0xFFFFFF] # Encodes color like 0xRRGGBB
  RGB_ORDER = 𝑆[ⴽ"[RGB]{3}"] # Weird modes like RRR only for testing purposes
  
  DEV = 𝐷[
    ?⟨"online"     ↦ 𝔹           ⟩, # Read-only
    ?⟨"NAME"       ↦ NAME        ⟩,
     ⟨"LEDC"       ↦ ℕ[x>0]      ⟩, # Units are in pxl, sorry if confusing
     ⟨"RGB_ORDER"  ↦ RGB_ORDER   ⟩,
     ⟨"REVERSE"    ↦ 𝔹           ⟩,
    ?⟨"RECALB_T"   ↦ ℕ[0≤x≤86399]⟩, # Daily reset time in seconds since UTC midnight.
                                    #   Results in the LED strip rotations jumping to some default position
                                    #   Generally should be 3AM local time
                                    #   Exists because due to floats having limited size and complicated math
                                    #     showing smooth nested rotation requires* unbounded percision
                                    #     (if α,β,γ∈ℝ⁺ and ℚ(α)≠ℚ(β): f(x∈ℝ⁺)=[αx%γ,αy%γ] is an injection)
                                    #     *lest one multiplies the big O by another factor of N
    ?⟨"AP_MODE"    ↦ 𝔹                       ⟩, # Write-only
    ?⟨"TOKEN"      ↦ TOKEN                   ⟩, # Write-only
    ?⟨"LEDP"       ↦ ℕ[valid esp32 pin]      ⟩, # Write-only
    ?⟨"BIT_TIMING" ↦ 𝑆[ⴽ"(\d{1,} ){3}\d{1,}"]⟩, # Write-only
    ?⟨"WS_URL"     ↦ 𝑆[valid URL]            ⟩, # Write-only
    ?⟨"UPDATE_URL" ↦ 𝑆[valid URL]            ⟩  # Write-only
  ]
  
  SCHEDULE = 𝐷[...*⟨ℕ[0≤x≤604799]↦SCENE_ACTIVATION⟩]
  
  ATOM_PARAM = ∪{
    [0,RGB], # Static
    [1,cyc:ℝ[0≤x≤100], sat:ℕ[x≤0xFF], val:ℕ[x≤0xFF]], # Rainbow
      # "cyc": Number of cycles, zero implies entire segment has the same color
      # "sat": Saturation
      # "val": Value (essentially brightness but better performance and maybe accuracy)
      # NOTE: The rotation of the containing MODE determines the speed of hue change
      #         It is tuned such that when the rainbow moves, the colors are interpolated
      #         such that the inner pixels do not jump. If cyc=0, then this does not occur.
      #         Is it not particularly intuitive how this translates when 0<cyc<1, so I advise
      #         against that range.
    [2,speed:ℝ[0<x≤100], sharp:ℝ[0≤x≤1], ...*(1≤len≤16)RGB] # Fade
      # "speed": color transitions per second
      # "sharp": determines the steepness of the curve.
      #          E.g.: sharp=0   ⇒ current color is always a mixure of two colors
      #                sharp=0.5 ⇒ colors are mostly static for a bit before
      #                              interpolating to next color.
      #                sharp=1   ⇒ colors do not interpolate (instantly change)
      #          The specific smoothing function can be seen at https://www.desmos.com/calculator/yli6q8tc25
  }
  
  EFFECT = ∪{
    [0], # Rev (Reverse)
    [1,speed:ℝ[0≤x≤100],offset:ℝ[-500≤x≤500]], # Rot (Rotation)
      # "speed" : measured in pxl per second
      # "offset": measured in pxls
    [2,ℝ[0≤x≤1]] # Lum (Brightness)
  }
  
  MODE = 𝐷[
    ?⟨"fx" ↦ *EFFECT⟩,
    ∪{
      ⟨"1"↦[pxl:ℕ[x>0], ...ATOM_PARAM]⟩,
        # A single atom with "pxl" pxls
      ⟨"*"↦[...*MODE]⟩
        # A grouping of multiple modes
    }
  ]
  
  SCENE = 𝐷[
    ⟨"offs"↦𝐷[...*(len>0)⟨UUID↦ℕ⟩]⟩,
      # The offset in pxl within the mode that each used device should take in
      #   order to seamlessly show a mode constructed out of multiple controllers
    ⟨"mode"↦MODE⟩
  ]
  
  SCENE_ACTIVATION = [
    NAME,
    ...∪{
      [que:true , dur:ℕ[>0]]
      [que:false, dur:∪{ℕ[>0],-1}]
    }
    # "que": Sets if the scene should be placed at the end of a que of effects.
    #        If false, then it is placed destructively at the front of the que.
    # "dur": If dur=-1, then it is infinite. Otherwise, it is time in ms.
    # que=true with dur=-1 is invalid
  ]

API:
  All API calls are JSON-encoded and sent as a POST request to "SERVER_URL/api"
  The body takes the following form:
  𝐷[
    ⟨"𝐭"↦TOKEN⟩
    ...∪{
      [
         ⟨"_"↦["Get_devs"]⟩ # returns 𝐷[...*⟨UUID↦DEV⟩]
      ],
      
      [
        ⟨"𝐔"↦*UUID⟩, # other than Get_devs all requests need a list of UUIDs
        ⟨"_"↦
          ∪{
            ["Change_dev"   , 𝐷[...*∪{...DEV}]   ],
            ["Set_scene"    , ...SCENE_ACTIVATION],
            ["Off"                               ],
              # Outputs a max buffer size (≥ LEDC) number of black pixels
            ["Del_scene"    , NAME               ],
            ["Push_scenes"  , 𝐷[...*⟨NAME↦SCENE⟩]],
            ["Pull_scenes"                       ],
              # Returns *𝐷[...*⟨NAME↦SCENE⟩]
            ["Set_schedule" , SCHEDULE           ],
            ["Pull_schedule"                     ]
              # Returns *SCHEDULE
          }
        ⟩
      ]
    }
  ]